<Layout title="Research · Guillermo Parada" prose={true}>
  <h1 class="page-title">Research</h1>
  <p class="page-lead">
    I work at the interface of RNA biology, machine learning, and neurogenomics, with a focus on
    how alternative splicing is regulated in the brain and how genetic variation disrupts RNA
    regulatory programs in neurodevelopmental disorders.
  </p>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    My research connects three complementary threads: (i) the systematic discovery and quantification
    of regulated splicing events — in particular microexons — from large-scale RNA-seq data; (ii)
    interpretable machine-learning models of the sequence and structural grammar that governs exon
    inclusion; and (iii) the integration of these molecular maps with human genetics to interpret
    disease-relevant variants. A common thread is reproducible workflow engineering that scales from
    single datasets to transcriptome-wide, cohort-scale analyses.
  </p>

  <h2>Microexons and neuronal splicing regulation</h2>
  <p>
    Microexons are very short exons whose inclusion is often tightly regulated across tissues,
    developmental stages, and neuronal cell types. My work has helped make systematic microexon
    discovery and quantification practical through <a href="/software/">MicroExonator</a>, and has
    connected microexon regulation to neuronal development and autism biology.
  </p>
  <p>
    Key themes include microexon discovery and quantification, neuronal alternative splicing,
    brain-enriched and developmentally regulated splicing programs, and autism-associated genetic
    variation affecting microexon regulation.
  </p>

  <h2>Machine learning for splicing and variant interpretation</h2>
  <p>
    I use machine learning to model the regulatory logic controlling microexon inclusion. The goal
    is to understand how local sequence context, splicing regulatory motifs, and disease-associated
    variants affect exon inclusion in brain-relevant transcripts, and to use these models for
    variant effect prediction.
  </p>
  <p>
    Key themes: interpretable machine learning for RNA regulation, sequence-to-splicing models, the
    regulatory grammar of neuronal microexons, and variant effect prediction for splicing.
  </p>

  <h2>RNA structure and alternative splicing</h2>
  <p>
    I have co-led work showing that RNA secondary structures can modulate alternative splicing at
    transcriptome scale. This includes G-quadruplexes and Alu-mediated RNA duplexes as regulatory
    layers that shape exon inclusion and primate-specific transcriptome evolution.
  </p>
  <p>
    Key themes: RNA structure as a splicing regulatory layer, G-quadruplexes, Alu-mediated RNA
    duplexes, and primate transcriptome evolution.
  </p>

  <h2>Reproducible computational biology</h2>
  <p>
    I care about building scalable and reproducible pipelines. My technical work uses Snakemake,
    Git, Conda, Unix/HPC environments, and GPU computing for machine-learning workloads, applied to
    bulk and single-cell RNA-seq, alternative splicing analysis, and RNA regulatory genomics.
  </p>

  <h2>Current and emerging directions</h2>
  <blockquote>
    Current work explores RNA regulatory mechanisms and transcriptomic signatures in brain
    disorders. I am interested in how RNA regulation, splicing, and genetic variation interact
    in neurodevelopmental disease.
  </blockquote>
</Layout>
